# Version & Changelog

Every meaningful code change must be reflected in `CHANGELOG.md` and `pyproject.toml`.

## Versioning rules (Semantic Versioning)

| Change type | Version bump | Example |
|---|---|---|
| Bug fix, minor correction | PATCH `0.x.Y` | `0.1.0` → `0.1.1` |
| New feature, new module implemented | MINOR `0.X.0` | `0.1.0` → `0.2.0` |
| Breaking interface change | MAJOR `X.0.0` | `0.1.0` → `1.0.0` |

During early development (0.x.x), MINOR bumps are used for each completed phase.

## When to bump

Bump the version and add a CHANGELOG entry when you:
- Complete implementation of a function that was previously `raise NotImplementedError`
- Add a new module, class, or public function
- Fix a bug in existing logic
- Change a public interface (function signature, data schema, env var name)

Do NOT bump for:
- Updating comments or docstrings only
- Reformatting code
- Adding or updating test stubs that are still skipped

## CHANGELOG format

Follow [Keep a Changelog](https://keepachangelog.com/en/1.1.0/):

```markdown
## [0.2.0] — YYYY-MM-DD

### Added
- Short description of what was added

### Changed
- Short description of what changed

### Fixed
- Short description of what was fixed

### Removed
- Short description of what was removed
```

Add new entries under `## [Unreleased]` as you work. When a version is ready to tag, move the `[Unreleased]` entries into a new versioned section and reset `[Unreleased]` to empty.

## pyproject.toml sync

When bumping, update the `version` field in `pyproject.toml`:

```toml
[project]
version = "0.2.0"  # ← must match the new CHANGELOG section
```

## Checklist before finishing any response that changes code

1. Does this change warrant a version bump?
   → If yes: update `version` in `pyproject.toml`.
2. Add a bullet under `## [Unreleased]` in `CHANGELOG.md` describing what changed.
3. Use past tense in CHANGELOG entries: "Added X", "Fixed Y", "Implemented Z".
